Dittus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Fritz, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bennette","meanings":["English (Cornwall): altered form of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennight","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Bene(i)t</i> + <i>-son</i>. See   Bennett   and compare   Benson  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Bennett was born about 1503, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs. William Bennett about 1527, in Chudleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1503–":"umbes 1503–Surnud","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1545–1570":"1545–1570","1528–1577":"1528–1577","1503–Male":"1503–Surnud","1503":"1503","1545":"1545","1577":"1577","1570":"1570","Abt 1528":"umbes 1528","Abt 1527":"umbes 1527","1528":"1528","1505":"1505","Abt 1503":"umbes 1503","of Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chudleigh, Teignbridge, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chudleigh, Devon, England","of Chudleight, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1503–":"noin 1503–Kuollut","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1545–1570":"1545–1570","1528–1577":"1528–1577","1503–Male":"1503–Kuollut","1503":"1503","1545":"1545","1577":"1577","1570":"1570","Abt 1528":"noin 1528","Abt 1527":"noin 1527","1528":"1528","1505":"1505","Abt 1503":"noin 1503","of Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chudleigh, Devon, England":"Chudleigh, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Chudleigh, Teignbridge, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chudleigh, Devon, England","of Chudleight, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1503–":"environ 1503–Décédé","1505–Female":"1505–Décédée","1545–1570":"1545–1570","1528–1577":"1528–1577","1503–Male":"1503–Décédé","1503":"1503","1545":"1545","1577":"1577","1570":"1570","Abt 1528":"envir